insert into cfg_5_2.requestdata (id, title, "Request_ID", "Status", "Project_Description", "CFG_Member?", "Requester_First_Name", "Requester_Last_Name", "447911925", "1339104825", "Assigned_First_Name", "Assigned_Last_Name", "Requester_Email", "Requester_Interest", "Request_Date", "Institution", "Shipping_Address", "CFG_Core", "Resource_Type", "Amount_Requested", "-1475790216", "-643239159", "2039874986", "GBP_being_Addressed", "5943919") values (42, E'cfg_rRequest_3073', E'cfg_rRequest_3073', E'Approved', E'The purpose of this request is to analyze recombinant zebrafish galectin-1, galectin-3 and galectin-9.', E'Yes subgroups :5 :Structural glycobiology ,7 :Glycomics and glycoinformatics ,3 :Glycans in cancer biology ,4 :Glycans in development and physiology ,1 :Glycans in host-microbe interactions ,2 :Glycans in immune recognition and function', E'Gerardo', E'Vasta', E'Gerardo', E'Vasta', E'Gerardo', E'Vasta', E'GVasta@som.umaryland.edu', E'Dr. Vasta\'s research focuses on the use of biochemical, molecular and structural approaches to the study of animal lectins and their carbohydrate ligands.', E'06/03/2014', E'Department of Microbiology and Immunology University of Maryland School of Medicine', E'IMET, Columbus Center 701 East Pratt Street Baltimore, MD 21202 Phone: 410.234.8826', E'H', E'MicroArray', E'', E'06/09/2014', E'Request to the CFG (Core H) for glycoarray analysis of galectins -1, -3, and -9 from zebrafish (Danio rerio) Gerardo R. Vasta, Ph.D. Professor Department of Microbiology and Immunology University of Maryland School of Medicine Program in the Biology of Model Systems IMET, Columbus Center 701 East Pratt Street Baltimore, MD 21202 Phone: 410.234.8826 Lab: 410.234.8827 E-mail: GVasta@som.umaryland.edu Background: Galectins are a family of carbohydrate-binding proteins that are widely distributed in nature having been identified in vertebrates, invertebrates, and protists. Members of this family are defined by their binding affinity for ß-galactosides and the presence of a conserved sequence motif within their carbohydrate recognition domain (CRD). Recent studies in mammals have demonstrated that galectins participate both directly and indirectly in mediating immune responses such as host-pathogen interactions, inflammation, and autoimmunity. We have shown that the galectins from invertebrate species such as the eastern oyster Crassostrea virginica and the protochordate Clavelina picta can recognize microbial pathogens. Given their evolutionary conservation, galectins may be part of an ancient mechanism of host defense. To gain insight into the origin and evolution of galectin function in immune responses and early development along the chordate lineages leading to mammals we characterized the galectin repertoire of the zebrafish (Danio rerio). We have recently discovered that the infectious hematopoietic necrosis virus (IHNV), a pathogen of the zebrafish (Danio rerio) and other teleost fish is recognized by the zebrafish galectins -1 (proto type), -3 (chimera type), and -9 (tandem repeat type) in a carbohydrate-dependent manner. Therefore, to gain detailed understanding of the molecular basis of this interaction it will be critical to obtain information about the specificity and biological role(s) of the zebrafish galectins. Although the Core H has previously analyzed samples of zebrafish galectins-1, -3, and -9, the binding to the glycan array has been very weak. In our laboratory, galectin samples from the same preparations bound strongly to asialofetuin in ELISA prior to their shipment to Emory, and we suspect that their binding activity was lost during transport. However, to ensure that the assay will be successful we have made new preparations, protected them from oxidative inactivation by carboxamidomethylation, and will be tested for binding to asialofetuin by ELISA on the same day prior to shipping. Significance: The biological roles of galectins have only been partly elucidated, encompassing embryogenesis and roles in innate and adaptive immunity mediated by the binding to endogenous and exogenous ligands. Like the oyster galectins CvGal1 and CvGal2, and the ascidian galectin CpGal16, the zebrafish galectins-1, -3, and -9 recognize exogenous ligands such as the glycosylated envelope of a viral pathogen. A detailed study through the glycan array at the CFG, aligned with Specific Aims 1 (Define the specificity and affinity for carbohydrate ligands) and 3 (Identify the ligand(s) that mediate GBP binding) should elucidate the carbohydrate specificity of the zebrafish galectins, and facilitate further studies by SPR and their crystallization in complex with the strongest ligands (Specific Aim 5: Determine the structures of selected GBPs). Analysis of the relationships between specificity and structure of galectins from taxa (invertebrates, protochordates and ectothermic vertebrates such as fish) ancestral to the mammals will contribute further to our understanding of the evolution of their roles in health and disease.', E'Y', E'Number of samples: We request glycoarray analysis of one sample of each recombinant zebrafish galectin-1, galectin-3 and galectin-9. Detection method: The zebrafish recombinant proteins are unlabeled. We will provide specific anti-galectin purified Igs. Detection method should be that routinely used by the Core H', E'* 1. Define the specificity and affinity for carbohydrate ligands * 3. Identify the ligand(s) that mediate GBP binding * 5. Determine the structures of selected GBPs');
