insert into cfg_5_2.requestdata (id, title, "Request_ID", "Status", "Project_Description", "CFG_Member?", "Requester_First_Name", "Requester_Last_Name", "447911925", "1339104825", "Assigned_First_Name", "Assigned_Last_Name", "Requester_Email", "Request_Date", "Institution", "Shipping_Address", "Comments", "CFG_Core", "Resource_Type", "Material_Requested", "Amount_Requested", "-643239159", "2039874986", "-1235327866", "GBP_being_Addressed", "5943919") values (52, E'cfg_rRequest_3050', E'cfg_rRequest_3050', E'Approved', E'The purpose of this request is to analyze secretory IgA from fecal material on the glycan array.', E'No', E'Joseph', E'Otto', E'Lewis', E'Pannell', E'Lewis', E'Pannell', E'jjo1201@jagmail.southalabama.edu', E'04/22/2014', E'University of South Alabama Mitchell Cancer Institute', E'N/A Protein-Glycan Interaction Core (formerly Core H)', E'Our lab focuses on biomarker discovery using mass spectrometry.', E'H', E'MicroArray', E'N/A', E'N/A', E'Cancer tissues can produce proteins with aberrant post-translational modifications in the form of glycans. We aim to explore the glycan binding potential of secretory IgA from fecal material. Antibodies have been shown in the past to bind glycans as specific cancer antigen, Muc16 (CA125) is an example. Proteomic analysis of patient samples has shown IgA to be the major component. We hope that by using a locally produced antibody, we can identify glycans associated with cancer for further investigation. We would like to start with a total of 6 samples: 2 from control patients, 2 from patients with adenomas, and 2 from colon cancer patients. We predict a difference in glycan binding profiles between healthy and diseased patient samples.', E'Y', E'David Smith, Core H Director', E'The antibody in these samples is secretory IgA from the human GI system. A secondary antibody against human IgA will need to be used for detection. Antibodies have been shown in the past to bind glycans as specific cancer antigen, Muc16 (CA125) is an example.', E'* 1. Define the specificity and affinity for carbohydrate ligands');
